INSERT INTO `atlasobject_facts` VALUES (1,1,'A bisonoric accordion is able to produce different pitches','A bisonoric accordion is able to produce different pitches. This is dependent on the direction the bellows are moved.'),(2,1,'Accordions are still made with a lot of human hands as opposed t','Accordions are still made with a lot of human hands as opposed to by machinery. Some parts are made by machine but the best are mostly hand made by craftsman.'),(3,1,'A unisonoric accordion will produce the same pitch regardless of','A unisonoric accordion will produce the same pitch regardless of the direction the bellows are moved. Size also plays a factor in the pitch.'),(4,1,'Pietro Deiro','Pietro Deiro, an Italy-born accordionist was known as the \'Daddy of the Accordion\'. He had a career in San Francisco during the vaudeville era and was even signed to RCA Victor Records.'),(5,1,'Accordion music can be found in Mexico','Accordion music can be found in Mexico, Brazil, Columbia, Europe, the United States, Canada, South America, and many other places.'),(6,1,'There were an estimated 75','There were an estimated 75,000 people in the United States in 1990 that could be classified as accordionists.'),(7,1,'The bellows are the section of cloth','The bellows are the section of cloth, cardboard, leather, and metal located in between the two manuals (keyboards and buttons). The bellows are expanded and contracted by the accordionist, which creates vacuum and pressure and drives air through the reed chambers to create sound.'),(8,1,'In the Soviet Union there was once a television show called \'Pla','In the Soviet Union there was once a television show called \'Play Your Accordion\'.'),(9,1,'The first to play the accordion in New York City\'s famous Carneg','The first to play the accordion in New York City\'s famous Carnegie Hall were Gene von Halberg, Abe Goldman, and Joe Biviano, in 1939.'),(10,1,'Weird Al Yankovic is a Grammy-winning parodist who incorporates ','Weird Al Yankovic is a Grammy-winning parodist who incorporates polkas into his music with his accordion. He was trained as a child to play the instrument.'),(11,1,'Accordions can be made with many different configurations','Accordions can be made with many different configurations.'),(12,1,'The accordion is able to sustain sound for a much longer time th','The accordion is able to sustain sound for a much longer time than most other instruments.'),(13,1,'Right-hand manual accordions can have a chromatic or diatonic bu','Right-hand manual accordions can have a chromatic or diatonic buttonboard, or a keyboard that looks like a piano.'),(14,1,'In other parts of the world the accordion has different names in','In other parts of the world the accordion has different names including the \'Sun-Fin-Chin\' in China, the \'bayan\' in Russia, the \'trekspill\' in Norway, and the \'Fisarmonica\' in Italy.'),(15,1,'The accordion has also been referred to affectionately as the sq','The accordion has also been referred to affectionately as the squeezebox.'),(16,1,'Several cities in the United States have designated the accordio','Several cities in the United States have designated the accordion as their official instrument including St. Paul, Skokie, and Detroit. San Francisco considers the piano accordion to be its official instrument.'),(17,1,'The accordion is used in pop music','The accordion is used in pop music, folk music, cajun music, jazz, classical, zydeco, and dance-pop.'),(19,9,'The first banjo name was \'strum strump\'','The first banjo description referred to the instrument as a \'strum strump\'. An English doctor was in Jamaica when he saw it and wrote about the banjo in his journal in 1687.'),(20,9,'Some famous banjoists include Steve Martin','Some famous banjoists include Steve Martin (actor, comedian and Grammy winning musician), George Crumb, Paul Elwood, Punch Brothers, Modest Mouse, and Beck. One of the most famous banjoists is Pete Seeger who plays with a longer-necked banjo.'),(21,9,'By the 1800s the banjo had been given 19 different spellings inc','By the 1800s the banjo had been given 19 different spellings including bonjoe, and banza. It is believed the word \'banjo\' is derived from the Yoruba word \'Bami jo\' which means \'dance for me\'.'),(22,9,'Banjo players are sometimes referred to as banjoists as well','Banjo players are sometimes referred to as banjoists as well.'),(23,9,'Six string banjos were invented by William Temlet in Britain who','Six string banjos were invented by William Temlet in Britain who sold banjos with as many as seven strings in 1846.'),(24,9,'The earliest written reference in North America to the banjo was','The earliest written reference in North America to the banjo was in 1736 in the New York Weekly Journal. In 1754 it was mentioned as a \'banjer\' in a Maryland newspaper.'),(25,9,'The duelling banjo piece in the 1972 movie Deliverance was actua','The duelling banjo piece in the 1972 movie Deliverance was actually recorded with a guitar and a banjo not two banjos. It is still one of the most famous banjo pieces known to the general public.'),(26,9,'Four string banjos include the plectrum banjo','Four string banjos include the plectrum banjo, tenor banjo, cello banjo, and the bass and contraband banjos.'),(27,9,'The first white banjo player to learn from African Americans was','The first white banjo player to learn from African Americans was Joel Walker Sweeney who lived from 1810 to 1860.'),(28,9,'He first company to manufacture banjos was owned by William Bouc','He first company to manufacture banjos was owned by William Boucher. In the 1850s Boucher won several awards for instruments including the banjo.'),(29,9,'The five string banjo is the most popular','The five string banjo is the most popular. Some musicians play with fingerpicks and a resonator but many prefer to use just their fingers.'),(30,9,'The five string banjo can be classic','The five string banjo can be classic, open back (common with old-timey music), or resonator with five strings. The five string banjo is still the most common.'),(31,9,'The banjo was used in the minstrel era when white entertainers d','The banjo was used in the minstrel era when white entertainers dressed up in blackface and portrayed African Americans in negative ways but the instrument managed to rise above the connotation of the minstrel era and remain a popular instrument in America.'),(32,9,'Banjos became extremely popular during the jazz age and in the 1','Banjos became extremely popular during the jazz age and in the 1940s guitars began to replace them.'),(33,9,'Banjos are traditionally made with a frame','Banjos are traditionally made with a frame, neck, and a head made of animal skin although plastic is more common now. Early banjos were made of a gourd shell, wood stick neck, and strings.'),(34,12,'In the orchestra setting the bass drum is suspended in a frame t','In the orchestra setting the bass drum is suspended in a frame that allows the drummer to change its position or angle. It is usually suspended by rubber straps or leather straps or wires.'),(35,12,'Adding the bass pedal to the drum kit made it possible for the d','Adding the bass pedal to the drum kit made it possible for the drummer to play other percussion instruments such as snare drums, as well as cymbals, because their hands were free to use smaller drum sticks.'),(36,12,'Bass drums are made with a shell (cylinder) that is usually made','Bass drums are made with a shell (cylinder) that is usually made of a type of wood (sometimes metal), with two heads (the part struck by the mallet or bass pedal) stretched over the two open shell ends.'),(37,12,'The sounds produced by the bass drum have been described as thun','The sounds produced by the bass drum have been described as thunderous, rumbling, pounding, hollow, mighty, and even soft at times.'),(38,12,'When the bass drum is part of a kit there are often other instru','When the bass drum is part of a kit there are often other instruments mounted to the shell including the cowbell, and the kit also includes tom-toms, cymbals, snare drums, high hats, and others.'),(39,12,'The mallets used for playing the bass drum (when not using a bas','The mallets used for playing the bass drum (when not using a bass pedal) usually have a thick handle often made of beech wood or hornbeam. The head usually has a wood core and is wrapped in felt material.'),(40,12,'Occasionally a timpani mallet is used for the bass drum when low','Occasionally a timpani mallet is used for the bass drum when lower dynamic sounds are desired.'),(41,12,'The inventor of striking the bass drum with a bass pedal was Wil','The inventor of striking the bass drum with a bass pedal was William F. Ludwig, in 1909, in Chicago, Illinois.'),(42,12,'Various other sticks are used for the bass drum including hard f','Various other sticks are used for the bass drum including hard felt sticks, leather sticks, wood sticks, side drum sticks, and brushes.'),(43,12,'Some of the most famous drummers include Neil Peart (from the ba','Some of the most famous drummers include Neil Peart (from the band RUSH), Buddy Rich, Ringo Star, Phil Collins, Benny Goodman, and Rick Allen (One-armed drummer for the band Def Leppard).'),(44,12,'When a bass drum is part of a drum kit it is placed on the floor','When a bass drum is part of a drum kit it is placed on the floor on feet, and the drummer hits the head with a bass pedal. Cloths are often used inside the head to dampen the sound.'),(45,12,'The bass drum as part of a drum kit (used in bands along with se','The bass drum as part of a drum kit (used in bands along with several other drums) was added in the beginning of the 1900s as part of jazz music.'),(46,12,'Most bass drums are stationary','Most bass drums are stationary, as in the drum kit set up. However when bass drums are used in marching bands they must be moveable and are suspended by straps or other apparatus to enable to drummer to walk with the instrument.'),(47,13,'French bassoons are referred to as buffets and do not have the i','French bassoons are referred to as buffets and do not have the ivory ring. They also sound different than the German bassoon.'),(48,13,'The parts of a bassoon include the bell joint','The parts of a bassoon include the bell joint, reed, crook, pads, bass joint, rod system, keys, wing joint, hand rest, and butt.'),(49,13,'Because the bassoon is a heavy instrument the bassoonist will of','Because the bassoon is a heavy instrument the bassoonist will often use a neck strap to help support its weight while playing.'),(50,13,'Bassoonists make their own reeds','Bassoonists make their own reeds, which is not necessary for most other instruments.'),(51,13,'The bassoon is often confused with the oboe','The bassoon is often confused with the oboe. They are both double reed instruments but are not the same at all.'),(52,13,'The bassoon\'s mouthpiece is made of metal and it is curved and j','The bassoon\'s mouthpiece is made of metal and it is curved and joined to the instrument\'s main part. The mouthpiece is referred to as a bocal or a crook.'),(53,13,'The price of a bassoon can range from $3000 to $25','The price of a bassoon can range from $3000 to $25,000 or more depending on the quality of the instrument. Because of its price and because of its difficulty in learning to play it is not usually the first woodwind instrument children learn to play in school. They usually start with a clarinet.'),(54,13,'The bassoon is known for its wide range','The bassoon is known for its wide range, distinctive tone, and warm sound that is comparable to a baritone male vocalist.'),(55,13,'In Italian the bassoon was originally referred to as a fagotto','In Italian the bassoon was originally referred to as a fagotto.'),(56,13,'The German bassoon is the most popular version of the instrument','The German bassoon is the most popular version of the instrument and is most common in North America while the French bassoon is more common in Belgium, France in South America.'),(57,13,'German bassoons have a white ivory ring at the bell joint\'s top ','German bassoons have a white ivory ring at the bell joint\'s top and these bassoons are referred to as heckles.'),(58,13,'The bassoon is a four foot long instrument','The bassoon is a four foot long instrument. The tube inside would stretch to eight feet if straightened out.'),(59,13,'To play the bassoon the bassoonist must use every finger and the','To play the bassoon the bassoonist must use every finger and their thumbs as well.'),(60,13,'The contrabassoon is considered to be the lowest pitched orchest','The contrabassoon is considered to be the lowest pitched orchestra instrument.'),(61,13,'Musicians considered to be notable bassoonists include Archie Ca','Musicians considered to be notable bassoonists include Archie Camden, Hugo Fox, Simon Kovar, William Waterhouse, and Julius Weissenborn, among many others.'),(62,13,'The reed of a bassoon\'s mouthpiece is an inch in width and longe','The reed of a bassoon\'s mouthpiece is an inch in width and longer than 2 inches. This makes the bassoon\'s reed one of the biggest instrument reeds used.'),(63,13,'Many composers have written parts for the bassoon including Joha','Many composers have written parts for the bassoon including Johann Sebastian Bach, and Ludwig van Beethoven.'),(64,13,'A musician that plays the bassoon is referred to as a bassoonist','A musician that plays the bassoon is referred to as a bassoonist.'),(65,13,'The word \'bassoon\' is derived from the French word \'basson\' and ','The word \'bassoon\' is derived from the French word \'basson\' and the Italian word \'bassone\'.'),(66,17,'The first bugle made in America is believed to be one by Nathan ','The first bugle made in America is believed to be one by Nathan Adams in 1825 in Massachusetts. This bugle can be seen in the U.S.S. Constitution collection at the Boston Naval Shipyard.'),(67,17,'During the Civil War in the United States the bugle was very com','During the Civil War in the United States the bugle was very commonly used for music as well as for battle and other military purposes. The bugle is mentioned in many of the letters that were sent home from soldiers.'),(68,17,'While early bugles did not have valves the more modern bugles do','While early bugles did not have valves the more modern bugles do have them. Without valves the bugler has to use their lips to change the pitch, and only the harmonic series of notes can be played.'),(69,17,'When used in the military the bugle can be an instrument for sig','When used in the military the bugle can be an instrument for signalling, but it also associated with being sounded right before charging the enemy.'),(70,17,'Bugle pitches include the high pitch (soprano bugle)','Bugle pitches include the high pitch (soprano bugle), medium pitch (alto bugle), tenor pitch (baritone bugle), and bass pitch (contrabass bugle).'),(71,17,'The half-moon bugle spread to England in the 1700s and began to ','The half-moon bugle spread to England in the 1700s and began to be used in the military there as well.'),(72,17,'The first time the bugle was used for signalling purposes in the','The first time the bugle was used for signalling purposes in the American Army was during the American Revolution.'),(73,17,'The first keyed bugles were invented in the early 1800s','The first keyed bugles were invented in the early 1800s. A patent was granted for the Royal Kent bugle in 1811 to Joseph Halliday in England. This version was used often until the 1850s.'),(74,17,'A person who plays the bugle is referred to as a bugler','A person who plays the bugle is referred to as a bugler.'),(75,17,'The first time a brass bugle was used for military purposes for ','The first time a brass bugle was used for military purposes for signalling was in 1758 in Hanover. It was called the Halbmondblaser (half-moon bugle). It had a U shape design which is how it got its name.'),(76,17,'Taps','Taps, the most famous US Military bugle call, was composed in 1862 by General Daniel Butterfield in Harrison\'s Landing, Virginia.'),(77,17,'The first bugles were either single','The first bugles were either single, double, or triple coiled instruments.'),(78,17,'There are more than 20 military bugle calls in the U','There are more than 20 military bugle calls in the U.S. Army.'),(79,17,'The bugle\'s limitations have resulted in it not being a common i','The bugle\'s limitations have resulted in it not being a common instrument in orchestras or other forms of music and it is most commonly associated with military use and Boy Scouts.'),(80,17,'Ancient Romans used the buccina - an instrument similar to the b','Ancient Romans used the buccina - an instrument similar to the bugle, for military purposes.'),(81,18,'The cajon can also be played in an orchestra as part of classica','The cajon can also be played in an orchestra as part of classical music.'),(82,18,'The word \'cajon\' means \'crate','The word \'cajon\' means \'crate, box or drawer\'.'),(83,18,'Early cajons were often made from shipping cartons brought over ','Early cajons were often made from shipping cartons brought over on Spanish ships in Spanish colonial America. Small dresser drawers were often converted to instruments as well whenever possible.'),(84,18,'Irish folk music has adopted the use of the cajon in much of its','Irish folk music has adopted the use of the cajon in much of its music.'),(85,18,'In modern music the cajon is often used as an accompaniment to t','In modern music the cajon is often used as an accompaniment to the acoustic guitar, and it is even used to replace full drum kits when space is limited.'),(86,18,'Five sides of the cajon are usually made of a thicker wood than ','Five sides of the cajon are usually made of a thicker wood than the front side where the musician slaps with his/her hand. The front side is thinner and is referred to as the head.'),(87,18,'The Peruvian National Institute of Culture declared the cajon Na','The Peruvian National Institute of Culture declared the cajon National Heritage in 2001.'),(88,18,'The Organization of American States declared that the cajon was ','The Organization of American States declared that the cajon was an \"Instrument of Peru for the Americas\" in 2014.'),(89,18,'The cajon is considered to be a percussion instrument','The cajon is considered to be a percussion instrument. I is usually 18 inches in height and about 12 inches wide and deep.'),(90,18,'When the musician sits on the cajon they tilt it slightly while ','When the musician sits on the cajon they tilt it slightly while playing. Some musicians also slap other surfaces of the cajon as well, to make different sounds than those that occur from slapping the front, or head, of the instrument.'),(91,18,'Cajons are popular instruments in Spain','Cajons are popular instruments in Spain, the Philippines, and in the Americas.'),(92,18,'Modern cajons have feet often made of rubber','Modern cajons have feet often made of rubber, and screws in the top of the instrument that allow for adjustment of sound.'),(93,18,'A bass drum sound is achieved by hitting the center of the front','A bass drum sound is achieved by hitting the center of the front, or head, and a higher tone is achieved by striking the instrument closer to the top of the head\'s surface.'),(94,18,'Hands are not the only striking tool for the cajon','Hands are not the only striking tool for the cajon. Musicians also use metal brushes, plastic brushes, sticks, mallets, and some use the drum pedal usually used for a bass drum.'),(95,18,'The cajon is gaining popularity in other types of music includin','The cajon is gaining popularity in other types of music including jazz, funk, rock, pop, and blues.'),(96,18,'Famous cajon players include Ruben Dantas (70s Flamenco music)','Famous cajon players include Ruben Dantas (70s Flamenco music), Mario Cortes (Flamenco), Mike Meadows (percussionist and drummer), Stephen Paass (percussionist), and Nina Rodriguez (nicknamed \'hands of lightning\').'),(97,18,'The cajon is a popular instrument in several music styles includ','The cajon is a popular instrument in several music styles including Cuban Rumba, Flamenco, Peruvian Waltz, Zamacueca, and Tondero.'),(98,19,'Smaller castanets produce a crisp','Smaller castanets produce a crisp, higher tone, while larger castanets produce a rich, mellow, lower tone.'),(99,19,'Some castanets are made for novelty purposes from materials that','Some castanets are made for novelty purposes from materials that are not suitable to produce the quality of sound desired by musicians. Novelty castanets are often made of bronze, silver, gold, marble, crystal, and even ivory.'),(100,19,'Women usually use the smaller castanets as the instrument should','Women usually use the smaller castanets as the instrument should fit in the palm of the hand. Men usually use the larger castanets because their hands can accommodate the larger size.'),(101,19,'When playing the castanets the musician rests one clapper of the','When playing the castanets the musician rests one clapper of the set in the palm of the hand, and links the string around their thumb. They use their fingertips to strike the other clapper of the set against the clapper resting in the palm to create sound.'),(102,19,'Castanets that are handcrafted for professional musicians are ma','Castanets that are handcrafted for professional musicians are made of more expensive materials such as hardwood or composite and cost much more - as much as $400 a set.'),(103,19,'Quality castanets are usually made of hardwoods such as oak','Quality castanets are usually made of hardwoods such as oak, pomegranate, ebony, rosewood, and granadillo.'),(104,19,'Although traditionally castanets were made in the shape of a con','Although traditionally castanets were made in the shape of a concave shell, today they are also made in other shapes such as rectangular, square, or even triangular.'),(105,19,'Many professional castanets today are made of synthetic material','Many professional castanets today are made of synthetic materials such as Micarta - a laminated material made similar to the method of creating fiberglass. Layers of fiber cloth are bonded with resin and heat and pressure are applied to create a product similar to hardwoods.'),(106,19,'The Spanish have other words for castanets as well including pul','The Spanish have other words for castanets as well including pulgaretes and platillos.'),(107,19,'Dancers use castanets to accompany their dancing but they are be','Dancers use castanets to accompany their dancing but they are being used in other music as well - even in orchestras today.'),(108,19,'Cheaper wood or plastic castanets are inexpensive and can be fou','Cheaper wood or plastic castanets are inexpensive and can be found for as little as $10.'),(109,19,'Some castanets are mounted on wooden handles','Some castanets are mounted on wooden handles, freeing up the musicians hands from the strings. Instead of strings they clappers are attached by elastic cords. This makes it easy for the musician to pick up the wooden handle and clap the castanets and set them back down quickly when not being played.'),(110,19,'Some musicians use other techniques to create sound with castane','Some musicians use other techniques to create sound with castanets as well.'),(111,19,'Castanets are referred to as pulgaretes when they are attached t','Castanets are referred to as pulgaretes when they are attached to the dancers\' thumbs.'),(112,19,'The sounds made by castanets comes from their size','The sounds made by castanets comes from their size, depth of hollow (or concave shape), and contact area at the tip of the castanet clappers.'),(113,19,'The word \'castanet\' is derived from the Spanish word \'castaina\' ','The word \'castanet\' is derived from the Spanish word \'castaina\' which means \'chestnut\'.'),(114,20,'The typophone had tuning forks instead of metal plates like the ','The typophone had tuning forks instead of metal plates like the celesta, which limited its sound and use.'),(115,20,'The celesta is also used in music styles other than orchestras a','The celesta is also used in music styles other than orchestras and classical music. It has been featured in jazz music by Earl Hines, Fats Waller, Duke Ellington, Oscar Peterson, and Herbie Hancock.'),(116,20,'The first major composer to use the celesta in a major symphony ','The first major composer to use the celesta in a major symphony work was Pyotr Tchaikovsky in his 1891 symphonic poem The Voyevoda.'),(117,20,'Famous works that have featured the celesta include Gustav Mahle','Famous works that have featured the celesta include Gustav Mahler\'s Symphony No. 6, George Gershwin\'s  An American in Paris, and Morton Feldman\'s For Philip Guston.'),(118,20,'The celesta does not produce loud sound and it does not have the','The celesta does not produce loud sound and it does not have the same dynamic range as a piano.'),(119,20,'The inventors of the celesta are considered to be Auguste Mustel','The inventors of the celesta are considered to be Auguste Mustel, a Parisian harmonium, and his father Victor Mustel. Auguste invented the celesta in 1886, from an earlier design of an instrument called the typophone, which his father Victor had invented in 1860.'),(120,20,'Tchaikovsky used the celesta in The Nutcracker - one of the most','Tchaikovsky used the celesta in The Nutcracker - one of the most famous ballets in history.'),(121,20,'The celesta is often combined with woodwind and high string inst','The celesta is often combined with woodwind and high string instruments, and the harp.'),(122,20,'The celesta is normally used for passages that are meant to soun','The celesta is normally used for passages that are meant to sound gentle and soft as it produces piercing music when played hard.'),(123,20,'The celesta was used for some of the music for the children\'s sh','The celesta was used for some of the music for the children\'s show Mr. Rogers\' Neighborhood.'),(124,20,'The celesta is similar to the glockenspiel but it has a warmer a','The celesta is similar to the glockenspiel but it has a warmer and rounder sound.'),(125,20,'Modern and contemporary','Modern and contemporary, pop, and rock musicians have also included the celesta in their music. These musicians and bands have included Buddy Holly, The Beatles, The Association, The Beach Boys, Rod Stewart, Pink Floyd, and Fiona Apple.'),(126,20,'The celesta was used for the song Pure Imagination that Gene Wil','The celesta was used for the song Pure Imagination that Gene Wilder sang in the movie Willie Wonka & the Chocolate Factory in 1971.'),(127,20,'The sound bars of the celesta are usually made from steel','The sound bars of the celesta are usually made from steel. The keys on the keyboard strike the hammers above, which strike the steel. The steel bars rest on hollow wood resonators. The sound is mellow, warm, and rich.'),(128,20,'Playing the celesta is similar to playing the piano with keys an','Playing the celesta is similar to playing the piano with keys and a pedal. The pedal is used when playing to prolong the notes\' sound.'),(129,28,'In Cuba the conga drum is referred to as tumbadoras and the cong','In Cuba the conga drum is referred to as tumbadoras and the conga drummer is referred to as a conguero.'),(130,28,'The conguero plays the conga drums with their fingers and the pa','The conguero plays the conga drums with their fingers and the palms of their hands and some use drum sticks or mallets but this method is less common.'),(131,28,'Some of the most famous music that incorporates the conga marcha','Some of the most famous music that incorporates the conga marcha includes Conga by Miami Sound Machine, Oye Como Va by Tito Puente, Virus by Bamboleo, and Watermelon Man by Mongo Santamaria.'),(132,28,'In a conga line','In a conga line, the dancers following the conguero are referred to as rumberos.'),(133,28,'The conga drum can be heard in a variety of Latin music styles t','The conga drum can be heard in a variety of Latin music styles today including salsa, Cuban jazz, merengue, songo, Latin rock and descarga.'),(134,28,'Conga drums are often played in sets of two to four but are not ','Conga drums are often played in sets of two to four but are not attached like bongo drums with a bridge.'),(135,28,'Cuban music is not the only style of music to incorporate the co','Cuban music is not the only style of music to incorporate the conga drum. It is also used in Dominican music, Colombian, Brazilian, reggae, funk, country, and samba music.'),(136,28,'There are five main strokes that congueros use when playing the ','There are five main strokes that congueros use when playing the conga drums. These include the open tone, muffled or mute tone, bass tone, slap tone, and the touch tone.'),(137,28,'When conga drums are being used as purely a percussion instrumen','When conga drums are being used as purely a percussion instrument they do not require tuning to a specific note. When played as part of the harmony in music they must be properly tuned to specific notes.'),(138,28,'Famous conga drum players come from a variety of countries inclu','Famous conga drum players come from a variety of countries including the U.S., Cuba, Brazil, Mexico, Puerto Rico, Haiti, and even Holland.'),(139,28,'In Cuba the tradition of playing the conga drums is passed from ','In Cuba the tradition of playing the conga drums is passed from one generation to the next.'),(140,28,'Conga drums are often made from wood or fiberglass and have a dr','Conga drums are often made from wood or fiberglass and have a drum head with screws for tuning.'),(141,28,'The ricardo is the smallest conga and has the highest pitch','The ricardo is the smallest conga and has the highest pitch, followed by the requinto, quinto, conga, the tumba; and the supertumba is the largest size conga drum and it also has the lowest pitch.'),(142,28,'Cubans often refer to the conga drum as the tumbadora','Cubans often refer to the conga drum as the tumbadora, which is the largest size of the conga drum when played in a set.'),(143,28,'The conga drum is a tall drum that is narrow and it is often pla','The conga drum is a tall drum that is narrow and it is often played while sitting in base (tripod).'),(144,37,'He drum kit can be divided into four main sections including the','He drum kit can be divided into four main sections including the hardware (drum stands, pedals, and cymbal stands), the extensions (chimes, tambourines, cowbells, other non-standard instruments), the shells (toms and bass drum), and the breakables (stool, snare drum, cymbals, sticks, and bass drum pedal).'),(145,37,'The cocktail kit is often only two pieces but the drums are ofte','The cocktail kit is often only two pieces but the drums are often regular size.'),(146,37,'The modern drum kit that most people recognize today was made po','The modern drum kit that most people recognize today was made popular in the 1920s in New Orleans in the Vaudeville era.'),(147,37,'The main components of the modern drum kit include the snare dru','The main components of the modern drum kit include the snare drum, toms, bass drum, octobans, ride cymbals, hi-hats, crashes, effects cymbals, and additional instruments such as cowbells, wood blocks, gongs, chimes, triangles, tambourines, timbales, brake drums, buckets, and tubular bells, and many others.'),(148,37,'The extended drum kit can include many more cymbals','The extended drum kit can include many more cymbals, drums, and additional instruments.'),(149,37,'The four piece drum kit with two hanging toms has two hanging to','The four piece drum kit with two hanging toms has two hanging toms and is common when space is limited.'),(150,37,'When a drum kit is shared between several drummers','When a drum kit is shared between several drummers, which happens if more than one band is playing on stage in one night, the \'breakables\' of the drum kit are usually swapped out between drummers so that they can use their own.'),(151,37,'The four piece drum kit with floor tom includes a floor tom','The four piece drum kit with floor tom includes a floor tom.'),(152,37,'Drum kits can come in different configurations such as three pie','Drum kits can come in different configurations such as three piece sets, four piece drum kit with floor tom, four piece drum kit with two hanging toms, five piece sets, cocktail kit, and extended kit.'),(153,37,'Drummers in the 1920s foley artists became important for silent ','Drummers in the 1920s foley artists became important for silent film makers. The drummer was the individual hired to create the sound effects for the films such as galloping horses, trains arriving, gun shots, and flying planes.'),(154,37,'The three piece drum kit is common for young drummers or when sp','The three piece drum kit is common for young drummers or when space is limited.'),(155,37,'Five piece drum kits are the most common drum kits and have thre','Five piece drum kits are the most common drum kits and have three toms in total and often have effects cymbals added.'),(156,37,'Jazz music','Jazz music, which included the drum kit, was a big part of the music in the depression era. It was a vital sound of the big band swing music.'),(157,37,'Drum kits first became popular military bands and then in jazz m','Drum kits first became popular military bands and then in jazz music.'),(158,37,'In the 1920s during prohibition the freelance drummer became pop','In the 1920s during prohibition the freelance drummer became popular.'),(159,37,'Well-known drum kit manufacturers include Gretsch Drums','Well-known drum kit manufacturers include Gretsch Drums, Ludwig-Musser, Pearl Drums, Yamaha Drums, Rogers Drums, Slingerland Drum Company, ddrum, Tama Drums, and Premier Percussion, and several others.');
